    "Background": {
      "text": "Air in the pericardium\nGenerally secondary to connection between pericardium and pleural cavity, bronchi, or GI tract\nMost often found following trauma, severe asthma exacerbation, strangulation, or forceful drug insufflation",
      "subsections": {
        "Causes_of_pneumopericardium": {
          "text": "GI malignancy\nPUD\nEsophageal diverticula\nBarotrauma\nMechanical ventilation\nVigorous bag-mask ventilation\nSCUBA diving/rapid ascent\nDrug insufflation (especially associated with crack\ncocaine\n)\nAsthma\nValsalva\nInfection\npericarditis\nwith gas-producing bacteria\nThoracic surgery\nPericardial fluid drainage\nBlast injury\nBlunt or penetrating\nthoracic trauma\nNeonatal\nrespiratory distress syndrome",
          "tables": []
        }
